@Node "Introduction" "ScreenSelect.guide/Introduction"
@Next "Installation"
@Prev "Main"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
************

   In version 2 of @{b}Amiga@{ub} operating system was introduced a concept of
Public Screens. These screens can be shared by application programs
just like Workbench screen has been in previous OS versions. Although
they bring a great addition to Amiga they also introduce a problem to
users which have Workbench, several Public and propably a few custom
screens open at the same time. And the problem is - "How to get that xxx
screen to front quickly without traversing through 5 other screens with
@{b}left-amiga m@{ub}?". Well, @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} is answer to that question because
it opens a small window to the active screen after hotkey selection
where you can select the new frontmost screen with just a click of the
mouse. Also you can make hotkey bindings to any screens (not just
Public ones as in older versions) and for example get Workbench screen
frontmost with only one key press. And the only requirement is that you
have @{b}Kickstart 2.04@{ub} (V37) or greater.


@EndNode

@Node "Installation" "ScreenSelect.guide/Installation"
@Next "ToolTypes and CLI usage"
@Prev "Introduction"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
************

   I have provided a script for Commodore's @{b}Installer@{ub} program so if you
have it then you should propably use it. Otherwise you can do following
actions.

   @{b}*@{ub} Move @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} to @{b}WBStartup@{ub} directory.

   @{b}*@{ub} Move @{b}ScreenSelectPrefs@{ub} to @{b}Prefs@{ub} directory.

   @{b}*@{ub} Move one of the doc files anywhere you normally store document
     files.


@EndNode

@Node "ToolTypes and CLI usage" "ScreenSelect.guide/ToolTypes and CLI usage"
@Next "Main Window"
@Prev "Installation"
@Toc "Main"

ToolTypes and CLI usage
***********************

   @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} recognizes normal commodity tooltypes and one of its
own.

@{b}CX_POPUP@{ub}
     This switch enables @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} to open its window when it's
     started.  Default is no popup.

@{b}CX_PRIORITY=xxx@{ub}
     This is @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}'s priority as commodity.  Here @{i}xxx@{ui} is decimal
     number. Default is 0.

@{b}CX_POPKEY=HOTKEY@{ub}
     Default is @{b}shift esc@{ub}. For example you could use @{b}CX_POPKEY=alt
     shift del@{ub} to change hotkey. If you specify popkey here you
     override the settings you have made with @{b}ScreenSelectPrefs@{ub} program.

@{b}PREFSPROGRAM=PATH@{ub}
     This is the path where preferences program is to be found. This
     name must include the name of the preferences program. Default
     PATH is @{b}SYS:Prefs/ScreenSelectPrefs@{ub}. see @{"Preferences" Link "Preferences"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Main Window" "ScreenSelect.guide/Main Window"
@Next "General Info"
@Prev "ToolTypes and CLI usage"
@Toc "Main"

Main Window
***********

   You can see the main selection window for @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} by pressing
the user configurable hotkey. This brings you a small window with few
buttons and a listview with names of open screens. Public screens all
have identifiable names but there are programs which use custom screens
and doesn't specify any name for it. Screens like that are shown as
@{b}(Nameless Screen)@{ub}.

@{b}Quit@{ub}
     By pressing button (or @{b}Q@{ub}) you can remove @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} and any
     patches it has installed.

@{b}About@{ub}
     This gives you a small info about this program and its author
     (that's me :^).

@{b}Prefs@{ub}
     This one opens the separate preferences program you can use to
     modify @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}'s behaviour. All changes come active instantly
     after you have exited preferences program with pressing either @{b}Save@{ub}
     or @{b}Use@{ub} buttons.

@{b}Update@{ub}
     This one updates the listview and default pubscreen texts to
     reflect current system state.  This is only usefull if you haven't
     installed @{b}Auto Update@{ub} patches.  You can install the patches with
     @{b}ScreenSelectPrefs@{ub} program.  see @{"Preferences" Link "Preferences"}.

@{b}Listview gadget@{ub}
     Click any of the names to get that screen to front. Single click
     just activates the name which you can then activate with @{b}Activate@{ub}
     gadget.  Double click makes an instant activation.

@{b}Default PubScreen@{ub}
     This one shows the name of the default pubscreen. If you have
     installed the @{b}Change Default PubScreen@{ub} hotkey you can use it to
     select active public screen as your default public screen.

@{b}Activate@{ub}
     Activates the current listview selection and closes the window.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Closes the window and returns back to the screen where hotkey
     selection was made.


@EndNode

@Node "General Info" "ScreenSelect.guide/General Info"
@Next "Preferences"
@Prev "Main Window"
@Toc "Main"

General Info
************

   There are few special options you can change with preferences
program.  Here are brief explanations about them. see @{"Preferences" Link "Preferences"}

@{b}Screen Types@{ub}
     Currently @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} can show only Public screens or all screens.

@{b}AutoUpdate Patches@{ub}
     This patches 4 Intuition functions to achieve automatic update in
     listview and in Default PubScreen textgadget. It also pretty much
     makes possible the use of QuickKeys because they automatically
     recognizes when screens are opened or closed. Patched functions
     are: OpenScreen, OpenScreenTagList, CloseScreen and
     SetDefaultPubScreen.

@{b}Window Position Modes@{ub}
     You can control the position of @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}'s main window with
     three possible options: @{b}Fixed@{ub}, @{b}Relative@{ub} and @{b}SmartPointer@{ub}.

     @{b}Fixed@{ub} mode forces window to always open to some predefined
     coordinates.

     @{b}Relative@{ub} always tries to position the window so that pointer is
     over the @{b}Activate@{ub} gadget.

     @{b}SmartPointer@{ub} first tries to position the window so that pointer is
     over the last selected screen name. If this isn't possible it then
     forces pointer to move there.

@{b}Window Autoactivation@{ub}
     You can set few options to control @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}'s behaviour with
     window activation.

     If you have @{b}Window AutoActivation@{ub} mode ON, it tries to activate
     window from screen you are changing to. It doesn't work most of
     the times because it just examines the windows and tries to be
     smart when deciding which window to activate.

     If also @{b}InputHandler@{ub} is ON, then @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} 'hears' all the
     changes with window actications. This helps you only with changes
     through @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}. If you change screen with @{b}left-amiga m@{ub}
     @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} has no way of knowing that you have switched to new
     screen except if you have added @{b}LoadView@{ub} patch.

     If @{b}LoadView@{ub} patch is active then @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} can hear all the
     screen changes and can always change new active window. As this
     one says it installs a patch to @{b}LoadView@{ub} function in
     graphics.library. It's a very time critical place and while I
     haven't confronted any problems, it might be a source of problem
     for users with heavy animation needs. If you encounter any
     problems with animations you should first try to take this off
     before starting to look problems elsewhere.

     So lets go all modes through one more time.  @{b}Window AutoActivation@{ub}
     activates autoactivation mode. @{b}InputHandler@{ub} option enables
     @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} to remember all changes with screens active windows
     and @{b}LoadView Patch@{ub} enables to hear all the frontmost screen
     changes. For best possible operation I suggest you to select them
     all.


@EndNode

