Main Prefs
==========

   After you have started @{b}ScreenSelectPrefs@{ub} you get a window very
similar to the system preferences program. All the actions from menus
and @{b}Save@{ub}, @{b}Use@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} buttons are exactly the same as in system
programs so they are not explained here. Please consult your AmigaDOS
manual for more info.

   However there are two buttons labeled as @{"Options" Link "Options"} and @{"Hotkeys" Link "Hotkeys"}.  These
are the buttons you should press to get one of the real preferences
change windows.


@EndNode

@Node "Options" "ScreenSelect.guide/Options"
@Next "Hotkeys"
@Prev "Main Prefs"
@Toc "Preferences"

Options
=======

   In this window are all the options settings.

@{b}Screen Types@{ub}
     Selects one of the operation modes. In @{b}Public Only@{ub} mode
     @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} uses only Public screens. In @{b}All@{ub} mode all screens are
     used.

@{b}Add AutoUpdate Patches@{ub}
     Toggles the state of AutoUpdate patches.

@{b}Window Position@{ub}
     Changes window position mode. Possible modes are @{b}Fixed@{ub}, @{b}Relative@{ub}
     and @{b}SmartPointer@{ub}. In @{b}Fixed@{ub} mode you can set the coordinate values
     to @{b}Left@{ub} and @{b}top@{ub} numeric gadgets.

@{b}Window AutoActive Options@{ub}
     You can select which level of AutoActivation you want. If you
     specify all three of them you get complete automatic window
     activation in your system. If Window AutoActivation is OFF then
     you can't select either @{b}Add InputHandler@{ub} or @{b}Add LoadView Patch@{ub}.

@{b}OK@{ub}
     This ones confirms all the changes and returns back to Preferences
     main window. Note that these changes are not used yet. You have to
     make global confirm with @{b}Save@{ub} or @{b}Use@{ub} buttons.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     This one cancels all the changes.


@EndNode

@Node "Hotkeys" "ScreenSelect.guide/Hotkeys"
@Next "StickySelect"
@Prev "Options"
@Toc "Preferences"

Hotkeys
=======

   In this window are all the hotkey settings.

@{b}PopUp Key@{ub}
     Used as hotkey for @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}. You can override this setting with
     CX_POPKEY tooltype.

@{b}Use Default PubScreen Key@{ub}
     Use the CheckBox gadget to toggle whether you want to use Default
     PubScreen key. If you do then write the hotkey to string gadget in
     right.

@{b}Add@{ub}
     Used to add new Screen Quickkey.

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     Used to delete selected Screen QuickKey.

@{b}Screen QuickKeys@{ub}
     List of screens you have set a Screen QuickKey for. Names can
     contain AmigaDOS patterns. For example @{b}TERM?@{ub} can mean @{b}TERM1@{ub} or
     possibly @{b}TERM2@{ub}. All standard AmigaDOS patterns are accepted.  This
     is great help when trying to make a QuickKey for some old programs
     using custom screens.

@{b}QuickKey@{ub}
     Hotkey for selected Screen QuickKey.

@{b}OK@{ub}
     Confirm changes.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Cancel changes.


@EndNode

@Node "StickySelect" "ScreenSelect.guide/StickySelect"
@Next "Misc"
@Prev "Hotkeys"
@Toc "Main"

StickySelect
************

   I have had several requests to enchange the interface to do some
operations differently. Because some of these have been contradictory
or in my opinion not something I like to add to @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} I have
made it possible for external programs to use @{b}ScreenSelect's@{ub} selection
mechanism. Now everybody can write a replacement for ScreenSelect's
interface.

   The first program to utilize this possiblity is @{b}StickySelect@{ub} which
opens a small window to any public screen with a list of selectable
names - just like the one in @{b}ScreenSelect's@{ub} interface. However this
window doesn't go away when you make a selection. Instead it just sits
there and wait's for new selection. You can open as many as you like to
different public screens as long as @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} is started before
@{b}StickySelect@{ub}. Here are the parameters.

@{b}PUBSCREEN=<>@{ub}
     Name of the Public screen you want @{b}StickySelect@{ub} to open.

@{b}LEFT=<>@{ub}
     Window left edge position.

@{b}TOP=<>@{ub}
     Window top edge position.

@{b}WIDTH=<>@{ub}
     Window width.

@{b}HEIGHT=<>@{ub}
     Window height.

   If you would like to implement your own interface to communicate with
@{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} you can contact me to obtain programming info and C source
for @{b}StickySelect@{ub}. see @{"Contact address" Link "Contact address"}.


@EndNode

@Node "Misc" "ScreenSelect.guide/Misc"
@Next "History"
@Prev "StickySelect"
@Toc "Main"

Misc
****

   This is a common procedure @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} makes when it hears about
hotkey selection.

         if hotkey pressed then
             if active screen is public screen then
                 lock it and open @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} window into it.
             else
                 lock default public screen and open window to it.

   So this means that @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} window isn't opened to foreign
applications screen. It's only opened to public screens. This may annoy
some users but I made this decision to make @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} more system
friendly. Remember that if you select new frontmost screen then there
really isn't much harm done. And even if you just press @{b}Cancel@{ub} gadget
you get always back to your old frontmost screen.

   @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} also tries to make sure that all screen pointers passed
back to OS, are always valid. This is easy with public screens but
requires little more work with normal screens. I hope I got it right!


@EndNode

@Node "History" "ScreenSelect.guide/History"
@Next "Contents of ScreenSelect distribution"
@Prev "Misc"
@Toc "Main"

History
*******

Version 1.0
===========

   First release 07-Sep-1992.

Version 1.1
===========

   This version was not released. Compilation date was 14-Sep-1992.

   @{b}*@{ub} Changed @{b}Workbench@{ub} tooltypes @{b}CX_POPUP@{ub} and @{b}ALLSCREENS@{ub} to simple
     switches. They are normally OFF, but if you specify one of them
     then that option comes ON.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}SMARTPOINTER@{ub} option. When this one is active @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}
     always tries to position mouse pointer over previous screen
     selection.  This makes it very easy to bounch between two screens.

     [ Suggested by Sfefan Boberg ]

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}QUICKKEYS@{ub}. Now you can bind own hotkey to every public
     screen. This should be used only with public screens. Although it
     might work with all screens I don't support it.

     [ Suggested by Stefan Boberg ]

   @{b}*@{ub} Now if @{b}ScreenSelect's@{ub} window is active (open) when hotkey is
     pressed then that window's screen is brought to front.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added menus to @{b}ScreenSelect's@{ub} window. Now most of the features are
     selectable with Menu command keys.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}About@{ub} window to show some information.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now previous screen's name is shown in listview gadgets selection
     area automatically. This makes screen bounching very easy as
     @{b}SMARTPOINTER@{ub} option does.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now @{b}Activate@{ub} and @{b}Cancel@{ub} gadgets have keyboard shortcuts.

     [ Keyboard shortcuts were suggested by David Corn ]

Version 1.1a
============

   Compilation date was 23-Sep-1992.

   @{b}*@{ub} Fixed a bug which happened when @{b}SMARTPOINTER@{ub} option was ON and
     screen font was too big to be used in @{b}ScreenSelect's@{ub} window and we
     had to use topaz80. This caused pointer to be moved to wrong
     position.

Version 1.1b
============

   Compilation date was 13-Oct-1992.

   @{b}*@{ub} Just changed a initial window height from 94 pixels to 96. Now
     normal topaz80 font shouldn't cause window resizing when only
     Workbench (or screen names of similar lenght) is in a list.

Version 1.2
===========

   Compilation date was 07-Dec-1992.

   @{b}*@{ub} Previously @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} exited when it couldn't find screens.
     This made it impossible to put it in @{b}Startup-Sequence@{ub} or
     @{b}User-Startup@{ub} file before @{b}Workbench@{ub} screen is opened.

     [ Reported by Andreas M. Kirchwitz ]

   @{b}*@{ub} From now on, version number format should be Amiga Style Guide
     compliant.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}AUTOACTIVATE@{ub} option.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}SCREENKEY@{ub} option which allows easy default public screen
     selection with hotkey.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}Default PubScreen@{ub} text gadget.

   @{b}*@{ub} First version compiled with SAS/C V6.1. Size reduced almost 2k
     compared to V1.1b.

Version 1.3
===========

   Compilation date was 27-Jan-1993. Not a public release.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now listview is opened as wide as widest screen name. This works
     correctly with proportional fonts too.

Version 1.4
===========

   Compilation date was 02-Feb-1993. Not released.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now gadget sizes are calculated before window is opened. So now
     @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} window opens to the correct size initially.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added @{b}LEFT@{ub} and @{b}TOP@{ub} tooltypes and CLI-parameters.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now if @{b}SMARTPOINTER@{ub} option is ON then @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} tries to
     position window according to the mouse pointer. And only if it
     fails to properly do so it moves mouse pointer to the correct
     position.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub} installs a input-handler to watch for
     WINDOWACTIVE messages, and we can properly activate right window
     when new screen is brought to front by @{b}ScreenSelect@{ub}.

Version 2.0
===========

   Compilation date was 08-Aug-1993. Major update.

   @{b}*@{ub} Whole interface code rewritten.

   @{b}*@{ub} Moved settings to separate preferences program.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added support for AmigaDOS patterns in QuickKey screen names.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added Relative Window Position mode.

   @{b}*@{ub} Moved all the patches to main program. Now patches are removable.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added LoadView patch.

   @{b}*@{ub} Added support for StickySelect.

   @{b}*@{ub} Possibly forgotten something, but changes were too big to describe
     them fully in here.


@EndNode

